<TITLE> Turk president vetoes government referendum plan </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ANKARA, June 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Turkey's President Ahmet Necdet Sezer on Monday vetoed a plan to cut the length of time needed to hold referendums, dealing a fresh blow to government efforts to shake up the constitution. The Islamist-rooted government, often at odds with the staunchly secularist Sezer, wants to hold a referendum on sweeping constitutional reforms on July 22, the same day as a general election. Sezer's veto now makes that much less likely. Turkey's secular elite, which includes top judges and army generals as well as Sezer and some opposition parties, is determined to block the ruling AK Party's reform plans. The government bill envisages cutting the time needed to hold a referendum to 45 days from 120 days. Parliament, now in recess ahead of the election, could still override the president's veto by approving the bill a second time unchanged. But Prime Minister Tayyip Erdogan has annoyed some in his ruling AK Party by deciding not to renominate them as candidates in the election, making it difficult to rally enough votes to push the law through again. Sezer was forced to agree on Friday to a referendum on the constitutional reforms after parliament overrode an earlier presidential veto. But few analysts now expect the reforms to take effect. Turkey's Constitutional Court is widely expected to throw out the reforms on a voting technicality when it rules on an opposition party appeal, possibly as early as Tuesday. The reforms include allowing voters, not parliament, to elect future presidents. Erdogan argues that the reforms will bring greater democracy. His critics say it will upset Turkey's delicate system of checks and balances. They fear the AK Party, Turkey's most popular, would win the presidency -- traditionally a bastion of the secularists -- in an open public vo
